# Software design

Use these expectations when shaping or changing systems. Adapt to your stack and domain.

## Boundaries
- Prefer clear module or service boundaries; minimize hidden coupling across layers.
- Expose narrow, stable interfaces; keep implementation details behind contracts you can evolve.

## Coupling and cohesion
- Group related behavior; avoid scattered duplicate logic and oversized “do everything” modules.
- Depend on abstractions where it simplifies testing, replacement, and reasoning.

## APIs and contracts
- Document or version breaking changes; prefer additive evolution when possible.
- Make success and failure modes explicit (errors, timeouts, partial results).

## Evolution
- Prefer migrations, feature flags, and staged rollouts over risky big-bang rewrites when impact is broad.
- Capture decisions that affect long-lived architecture (short design notes or ADRs).

## Tradeoffs
- State the tradeoff when choosing performance, simplicity, time-to-ship, or flexibility.
- Revisit assumptions when scale, usage, or failure modes change.
